  "response": "South Korean high schools are known for their intense academic environment. Here are some key characteristics:\n\n1. Academic Pressure\n- Extremely competitive\n- Long study hours (often 12-16 hours per day)\n- Strong emphasis on college entrance exams (\uc218\ub2a5, Suneung)\n- High-stakes testing and academic performance\n\n2. Schedule\n- School typically runs from 8am to 4-5pm\n- Many students attend after-school academies (\ud559\uc6d0, hagwon) until late evening\n- Some students study at school until 10pm or later\n\n3. Culture\n- Strict discipline and uniforms\n- Respect for teachers is very important\n- Strong peer competition\n- Group-oriented social dynamics\n\n4. Extracurricular Activities\n- Limited compared to Western schools\n- More focus on academic achievement\n- Some sports and club activities exist\n\n5. Technology\n- Advanced technology in classrooms\n- Many schools have computer labs and digital resources\n\n6. Curriculum\n- Emphasis on math, science, and language subjects\n- Comprehensive preparation for university entrance exams\n- Less focus on arts and creative subjects\n\nThese characteristics reflect South Korea's highly competitive educational culture and strong societal value placed on academic success.",
